classitems.description:
Makes a request out of a URI-like request string. This is intended to
be used where a fragment id (after a URI '#') is parsed as a URI with
path and query parts. The string should have a path beginning and
delimited by '/' and optional query parameters following a '?'. The
query should be a standard URL set of key value pairs delimited by
'&'. For backwards compatibility the initial '/' on the path is not
required. The request object has the following API, (fully described
in the method code):
   {
      path: <the path string part>.
      query: <the query string part>,
      getPath(i): get part or all of the split path array,
      getQuery(k, i): get part or all of a query key array,
      getQueryLast(k, _default): get last element of a query key array.
   }
Get path or element in path.

Copyright (c) 2010-2014 Digital Bazaar, Inc.

The only algorithm currently supported for PKI is RSA.

An RSA key is often stored in ASN.1 DER format. The SubjectPublicKeyInfo
ASN.1 structure is composed of an algorithm of type AlgorithmIdentifier
and a subjectPublicKey of type bit string.

The AlgorithmIdentifier contains an Object Identifier (OID) and parameters
for the algorithm, if any. In the case of RSA, there aren't any.

SubjectPublicKeyInfo ::= SEQUENCE {
  algorithm AlgorithmIdentifier,
  subjectPublicKey BIT STRING
}

AlgorithmIdentifer ::= SEQUENCE {
  algorithm OBJECT IDENTIFIER,
  parameters ANY DEFINED BY algorithm OPTIONAL
}

For an RSA public key, the subjectPublicKey is:

RSAPublicKey ::= SEQUENCE {
  modulus            INTEGER,    -- n
  publicExponent     INTEGER     -- e
}

PrivateKeyInfo ::= SEQUENCE {
  version                   Version,
  privateKeyAlgorithm       PrivateKeyAlgorithmIdentifier,
  privateKey                PrivateKey,
  attributes           [0]  IMPLICIT Attributes OPTIONAL
}

Version ::= INTEGER
PrivateKeyAlgorithmIdentifier ::= AlgorithmIdentifier
PrivateKey ::= OCTET STRING
Attributes ::= SET OF Attribute

An RSA private key as the following structure:

RSAPrivateKey ::= SEQUENCE {
  version Version,
  modulus INTEGER, -- n
  publicExponent INTEGER, -- e
  privateExponent INTEGER, -- d
  prime1 INTEGER, -- p
  prime2 INTEGER, -- q
  exponent1 INTEGER, -- d mod (p-1)
  exponent2 INTEGER, -- d mod (q-1)
  coefficient INTEGER -- (inverse of q) mod p
}

Version ::= INTEGER

The OID for the RSA key algorithm is: 1.2.840.113549.1.1.1

classitems.description:
Wrap digest in DigestInfo object.

This function implements EMSA-PKCS1-v1_5-ENCODE as per RFC 3447.

DigestInfo ::= SEQUENCE {
  digestAlgorithm DigestAlgorithmIdentifier,
  digest Digest
}

DigestAlgorithmIdentifier ::= AlgorithmIdentifier
Digest ::= OCTET STRING

params.name: md
params.description: the message digest object with the hash to sign.

return.description: the encoded message (ready for RSA encrytion)

params.name: x
params.description: the number to raise and mod.

params.name: key
params.description: the key to use.

params.name: pub
params.description: true if the key is public, false if private.

return.description: the result of x^c mod n.

classitems.description:
NOTE: THIS METHOD IS DEPRECATED, use 'sign' on a private key object or
'encrypt' on a public key object instead.

Performs RSA encryption.

The parameter bt controls whether to put padding bytes before the
message passed in. Set bt to either true or false to disable padding
completely (in order to handle e.g. EMSA-PSS encoding seperately before),
signaling whether the encryption operation is a public key operation
(i.e. encrypting data) or not, i.e. private key operation (data signing).

For PKCS#1 v1.5 padding pass in the block type to use, i.e. either 0x01
(for signing) or 0x02 (for encryption). The key operation mode (private
or public) is derived from this flag in that case).

params.name: m
params.description: the message to encrypt as a byte string.

params.name: key
params.description: the RSA key to use.

params.name: bt
params.description:
for PKCS#1 v1.5 padding, the block type to use
  (0x01 for private key, 0x02 for public),
  to disable padding: true = public key, false = private key.

return.description: the encrypted bytes as a string.

classitems.description:
NOTE: THIS METHOD IS DEPRECATED, use 'decrypt' on a private key object or
'verify' on a public key object instead.

Performs RSA decryption.

The parameter ml controls whether to apply PKCS#1 v1.5 padding
or not.  Set ml = false to disable padding removal completely
(in order to handle e.g. EMSA-PSS later on) and simply pass back
the RSA encryption block.

params.name: ed
params.description: the encrypted data to decrypt in as a byte string.

params.name: key
params.description: the RSA key to use.

params.name: pub
params.description: true for a public key operation, false for private.

params.name: ml
params.description: the message length, if known, false to disable padding.

return.description: the decrypted message as a byte string.

classitems.description:
Creates an RSA key-pair generation state object. It is used to allow
key-generation to be performed in steps. It also allows for a UI to
display progress updates.

params.name: bits
params.description: the size for the private key in bits, defaults to 2048.

params.name: e
params.description: the public exponent to use, defaults to 65537 (0x10001).

params.name: options
params.description:
the options to use.
         prng a custom crypto-secure pseudo-random number generator to use,
           that must define "getBytesSync".
         algorithm the algorithm to use (default: 'PRIMEINC').

return.description: the state object to use to generate the key-pair.

params.name: state
params.description: the state to use.

params.name: n
params.description:
the maximum number of milliseconds to run the algorithm for, 0
         to run the algorithm to completion.

return.description: true if the key-generation completed, false if not.

classitems.description:
Generates an RSA public-private key pair in a single call.

To generate a key-pair in steps (to allow for progress updates and to
prevent blocking or warnings in slow browsers) then use the key-pair
generation state functions.

To generate a key-pair asynchronously (either through web-workers, if
available, or by breaking up the work on the main thread), pass a
callback function.

params.name: bits
params.description: the size for the private key in bits, defaults to 2048.

params.name: e
params.description: the public exponent to use, defaults to 65537.

params.name: options
params.description:
options for key-pair generation, if given then 'bits'
         and 'e' must *not* be given:
         bits the size for the private key in bits, (default: 2048).
         e the public exponent to use, (default: 65537 (0x10001)).
         workerScript the worker script URL.
         workers the number of web workers (if supported) to use,
           (default: 2).
         workLoad the size of the work load, ie: number of possible prime
           numbers for each web worker to check per work assignment,
           (default: 100).
         e the public exponent to use, defaults to 65537.
         prng a custom crypto-secure pseudo-random number generator to use,
           that must define "getBytesSync".
         algorithm the algorithm to use (default: 'PRIMEINC').

params.name: callback(err, keypair)
params.description: called once the operation completes.

return.description: an object with privateKey and publicKey properties.

classitems.description:
Verifies the given signature against the given digest.

PKCS#1 supports multiple (currently two) signature schemes:
RSASSA-PKCS1-V1_5 and RSASSA-PSS.

By default this implementation uses the "old scheme", i.e.
RSASSA-PKCS1-V1_5, in which case once RSA-decrypted, the
signature is an OCTET STRING that holds a DigestInfo.

DigestInfo ::= SEQUENCE {
  digestAlgorithm DigestAlgorithmIdentifier,
  digest Digest
}
DigestAlgorithmIdentifier ::= AlgorithmIdentifier
Digest ::= OCTET STRING

To perform PSS signature verification, provide an instance
of Forge PSS object as the scheme parameter.

params.name: digest
params.description:
the message digest hash to compare against the signature,
         as a binary-encoded string.

params.name: signature
params.description: the signature to verify, as a binary-encoded string.

params.name: scheme
params.description:
signature verification scheme to use:
         'RSASSA-PKCS1-V1_5' or undefined for RSASSA PKCS#1 v1.5,
         a Forge PSS object for RSASSA-PSS,
         'NONE' or null for none, DigestInfo will not be expected, but
           PKCS#1 v1.5 padding will still be used.

return.description: true if the signature was verified, false if not.

classitems.description:
Signs the given digest, producing a signature.

PKCS#1 supports multiple (currently two) signature schemes:
RSASSA-PKCS1-V1_5 and RSASSA-PSS.

By default this implementation uses the "old scheme", i.e.
RSASSA-PKCS1-V1_5. In order to generate a PSS signature, provide
an instance of Forge PSS object as the scheme parameter.

params.name: md
params.description: the message digest object with the hash to sign.

params.name: scheme
params.description:
the signature scheme to use:
         'RSASSA-PKCS1-V1_5' or undefined for RSASSA PKCS#1 v1.5,
         a Forge PSS object for RSASSA-PSS,
         'NONE' or null for none, DigestInfo will not be used but
           PKCS#1 v1.5 padding will still be used.

return.description: the signature as a byte string.

classitems.description:
Starts or restarts the encryption or decryption process, whichever
was previously configured.

For non-GCM mode, the IV may be a binary-encoded string of bytes, an array
of bytes, a byte buffer, or an array of 32-bit integers. If the IV is in
bytes, then it must be Nb (16) bytes in length. If the IV is given in as
32-bit integers, then it must be 4 integers long.

Note: an IV is not required or used in ECB mode.

For GCM-mode, the IV must be given as a binary-encoded string of bytes or
a byte buffer. The number of bytes should be 12 (96 bits) as recommended
by NIST SP-800-38D but another length may be given.

params.name: options
params.description:
the options to use:
         iv the initialization vector to use as a binary-encoded string of
           bytes, null to reuse the last ciphered block from a previous
           update() (this "residue" method is for legacy support only).
         additionalData additional authentication data as a binary-encoded
           string of bytes, for 'GCM' mode, (default: none).
         tagLength desired length of authentication tag, in bits, for
           'GCM' mode (0-128, default: 128).
         tag the authentication tag to check if decrypting, as a
            binary-encoded string of bytes.
         output the output the buffer to write to, null to create one.

classitems.description: Updates the next block according to the cipher mode.

params.name: input
params.description: the buffer to read from.

classitems.description: Finishes encrypting or decrypting.

params.name: pad
params.description:
a padding function to use in CBC mode, null for default,
         signature(blockSize, buffer, decrypt).

return.description: true if successful, false on error.

the type to be defined in @context.
classitems.name: getFullType

classitems.description:
Also could be called "upcast", for those in the know.

Ghetto method of copying properties from some other object. As freshly
deserialized javascript objects do not inherently attach the functions of
their type, it is this or factory hell.
classitems.name: copyFrom

params.name: that
params.description: The freshly deserialized object, or the object to upcast into this object.

classitems.description: Upgrades the object to the latest version, performing transforms and the like.
classitems.name: upgrade

classitems.description:
Removes the @ symbol from properties in order to make them more
accessible in Javascript.
classitems.name: deAtify

return.description: This object, with @ properties converted to @-less properties.

classitems.description: Gets all versions of JSON-LD type strings for this type of object.
classitems.name: getTypes

classitems.description:
Schema.org/name
The name of the item.
classitems.name: name

classitems.description:
Schema.org/identifier
The identifier property represents any kind of identifier for any kind of [[Thing]], such as ISBNs, GTIN codes, UUIDs etc. Schema.org provides dedicated properties for representing many of these, either as textual strings or as URL (URI) links. See [background notes](/docs/datamodel.html#identifierBg) for more details.
classitems.name: identifier

classitems.description:
Schema.org/url
URL of the item.
classitems.name: url

classitems.description:
Schema.org/image
An image of the item. This can be a [[URL]] or a fully described [[ImageObject]].
classitems.name: image

classitems.description:
Schema.org/description
A description of the item.
classitems.name: description

classitems.description:
Schema.org/disambiguatingDescription
A sub property of description. A short description of the item used to disambiguate from other, similar items. Information from other properties (in particular, name) may be necessary for the description to be useful for disambiguation.
classitems.name: disambiguatingDescription

classitems.description:
Schema.org/alternateName
An alias for the item.
classitems.name: alternateName

classitems.description:
Schema.org/sameAs
URL of a reference Web page that unambiguously indicates the item's identity. E.g. the URL of the item's Wikipedia page, Wikidata entry, or official website.
classitems.name: sameAs

classitems.description:
Schema.org/additionalType
An additional type for the item, typically used for adding more specific types from external vocabularies in microdata syntax. This is a relationship between something and a class that the thing is in. In RDFa syntax, it is better to use the native RDFa syntax - the 'typeof' attribute - for multiple types. Schema.org tools may have only weaker understanding of extra types, in particular those defined externally.
classitems.name: additionalType

classitems.description:
Schema.org/potentialAction
Indicates a potential Action, which describes an idealized action in which this thing would play an 'object' role.
classitems.name: potentialAction

classitems.description:
Schema.org/mainEntityOfPage
Indicates a page (or other CreativeWork) for which this thing is the main entity being described. See [background notes](/docs/datamodel.html#mainEntityBackground) for details.
classitems.name: mainEntityOfPage

classitems.description: Method to set Thing name
classitems.name: setName

params.name: name
params.description: Name to set for this Thing

classitems.description: Returns the name of the thing
classitems.name: getName

classitems.description: Method to set Thing description
classitems.name: setDescription

params.name: description
params.description: Description to set for its Thing

classitems.description: Returns the description of the thing
classitems.name: getDescription

classitems.description:

Review of the item.
classitems.name: reviews

classitems.description:
Schema.org/amenityFeature
An amenity feature (e.g. a characteristic or service) of the Accommodation. This generic property does not make a statement about whether the feature is included in an offer for the main accommodation or available at extra costs.
classitems.name: amenityFeature

classitems.description:

Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.
classitems.name: event

classitems.description:

The fax number.
classitems.name: faxNumber

classitems.description:
Schema.org/additionalProperty
A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.
classitems.name: additionalProperty

classitems.name: isicV4

The opening hours of a certain place.
classitems.name: openingHoursSpecification

Photographs of this place.
classitems.name: photos

classitems.description:

A URL to a map of the place.
classitems.name: map

classitems.description:
Schema.org/hasMap
A URL to a map of the place.
classitems.name: hasMap

classitems.description:
Schema.org/smokingAllowed
Indicates whether it is allowed to smoke in the place, e.g. in the restaurant, hotel or hotel room.
classitems.name: smokingAllowed

classitems.description:

The telephone number.

classitems.description:

classitems.description:

The special opening hours of a certain place.\n\nUse this to explicitly override general opening hours brought in scope by [[openingHoursSpecification]] or [[openingHours]].
classitems.name: specialOpeningHoursSpecification

classitems.description:
Schema.org/branchCode
A short textual code (also called "store code") that uniquely identifies a place of business. The code is typically assigned by the parentOrganization and used in structured URLs.\n\nFor example, in the URL http://www.starbucks.co.uk/store-locator/etc/detail/3047 the code "3047" is a branchCode for a particular branch.
classitems.name: branchCode

classitems.description:
Schema.org/logo

classitems.description:

The [Global Location Number](http://www.gs1.org/gln) (GLN, sometimes also referred to as International Location Number or ILN) of the respective organization, person, or place. The GLN is a 13-digit number used to identify parties and physical locations.
classitems.name: globalLocationNumber

Gender of the person. While http://schema.org/Male and http://schema.org/Female may be used, text strings are also acceptable for people who do not identify as a binary gender.

A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

The [Global Location Number](http://www.gs1.org/gln) (GLN, sometimes also referred to as International Location Number or ILN) of the respective organization, person, or place. The GLN is a 13-digit number used to identify parties and physical locations.

An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.
classitems.name: audience

Approximate or typical time it takes to work with or through this learning resource for the typical intended target audience, e.g. 'P30M', 'P1H25M'.
classitems.name: timeRequired

A publication event associated with the item.

classitems.description:

An award won by or for this item.
classitems.name: award

classitems.description:
Schema.org/contentLocation
The location depicted or described in the content. For example, the location in a photograph or painting.
classitems.name: contentLocation

classitems.description:
Schema.org/temporalCoverage
The temporalCoverage of a CreativeWork indicates the period that the content applies to, i.e. that it describes, either as a DateTime or as a textual string indicating a time period in [ISO 8601 time interval format](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601#Time_intervals). In
     the case of a Dataset it will typically indicate the relevant time period in a precise notation (e.g. for a 2011 census dataset, the year 2011 would be written "2011/2012"). Other forms of content e.g. ScholarlyArticle, Book, TVSeries or TVEpisode may indicate their temporalCoverage in broader terms - textually or via well-known URL.
     Written works such as books may sometimes have precise temporal coverage too, e.g. a work set in 1939 - 1945 can be indicated in ISO 8601 interval format format via "1939/1945".
classitems.name: temporalCoverage

classitems.description:
Schema.org/isBasedOn
A resource that was used in the creation of this resource. This term can be repeated for multiple sources. For example, http://example.com/great-multiplication-intro.html.
classitems.name: isBasedOn

classitems.description:
Schema.org/headline
Headline of the article.
classitems.name: headline

classitems.description:
Schema.org/fileFormat
Media type, typically MIME format (see [IANA site](http://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml)) of the content e.g. application/zip of a SoftwareApplication binary. In cases where a CreativeWork has several media type representations, 'encoding' can be used to indicate each MediaObject alongside particular fileFormat information. Unregistered or niche file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia entry.
classitems.name: fileFormat

classitems.description:
Schema.org/interactionStatistic
The number of interactions for the CreativeWork using the WebSite or SoftwareApplication. The most specific child type of InteractionCounter should be used.
classitems.name: interactionStatistic

classitems.description:
Schema.org/recordedAt
The Event where the CreativeWork was recorded. The CreativeWork may capture all or part of the event.
classitems.name: recordedAt

classitems.description:
Schema.org/isAccessibleForFree
A flag to signal that the publication is accessible for free.
classitems.name: isAccessibleForFree

classitems.description:
Schema.org/isPartOf
Indicates a CreativeWork that this CreativeWork is (in some sense) part of.
classitems.name: isPartOf

classitems.description:
Schema.org/exampleOfWork
A creative work that this work is an example/instance/realization/derivation of.
classitems.name: exampleOfWork

classitems.description:
Schema.org/accessibilityFeature
Content features of the resource, such as accessible media, alternatives and supported enhancements for accessibility ([WebSchemas wiki lists possible values](http://www.w3.org/wiki/WebSchemas/Accessibility)).
classitems.name: accessibilityFeature

classitems.description:
Schema.org/dateCreated
The date on which the CreativeWork was created or the item was added to a DataFeed.
classitems.name: dateCreated

classitems.description:
Schema.org/releasedEvent
The place and time the release was issued, expressed as a PublicationEvent.
classitems.name: releasedEvent

classitems.description:
Schema.org/publisher
The publisher of the creative work.
classitems.name: publisher

classitems.description:
Schema.org/accessibilityControl
Identifies input methods that are sufficient to fully control the described resource ([WebSchemas wiki lists possible values](http://www.w3.org/wiki/WebSchemas/Accessibility)).
classitems.name: accessibilityControl

classitems.description:
Schema.org/isFamilyFriendly
Indicates whether this content is family friendly.
classitems.name: isFamilyFriendly

classitems.description:

A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for associatedMedia.
classitems.name: encoding

classitems.description:
Schema.org/alternativeHeadline
A secondary title of the CreativeWork.
classitems.name: alternativeHeadline

classitems.description:
Schema.org/educationalUse
The purpose of a work in the context of education; for example, 'assignment', 'group work'.
classitems.name: educationalUse

classitems.description:
Schema.org/creator
The creator/author of this CreativeWork. This is the same as the Author property for CreativeWork.
classitems.name: creator

classitems.description:
Schema.org/hasPart
Indicates a CreativeWork that is (in some sense) a part of this CreativeWork.
classitems.name: hasPart

classitems.description:
Schema.org/license
A license document that applies to this content, typically indicated by URL.
classitems.name: license

classitems.description:
Schema.org/translator
Organization or person who adapts a creative work to different languages, regional differences and technical requirements of a target market, or that translates during some event.
classitems.name: translator

classitems.description:
Schema.org/offers
An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event.
classitems.name: offers

classitems.description:
Schema.org/publishingPrinciples
Link to page describing the editorial principles of the organization primarily responsible for the creation of the CreativeWork.
classitems.name: publishingPrinciples

classitems.description:
Schema.org/schemaVersion
Indicates (by URL or string) a particular version of a schema used in some CreativeWork. For example, a document could declare a schemaVersion using an URL such as http://schema.org/version/2.0/ if precise indication of schema version was required by some application.
classitems.name: schemaVersion

classitems.description:
Schema.org/review
A review of the item.
classitems.name: review

classitems.description:
Schema.org/position
The position of an item in a series or sequence of items.
classitems.name: position

classitems.description:
Schema.org/accessMode
The human sensory perceptual system or cognitive faculty through which a person may process or perceive information. Expected values include: auditory, tactile, textual, visual, colorDependent, chartOnVisual, chemOnVisual, diagramOnVisual, mathOnVisual, musicOnVisual, textOnVisual.
classitems.name: accessMode

classitems.description:
Schema.org/genre
Genre of the creative work, broadcast channel or group.
classitems.name: genre

classitems.description:
Schema.org/character
Fictional person connected with a creative work.
classitems.name: character

classitems.description:
Schema.org/commentCount
The number of comments this CreativeWork (e.g. Article, Question or Answer) has received. This is most applicable to works published in Web sites with commenting system; additional comments may exist elsewhere.
classitems.name: commentCount

classitems.description:
Schema.org/contentRating
Official rating of a piece of content—for example,'MPAA PG-13'.
classitems.name: contentRating

classitems.description:
Schema.org/awards
Awards won by or for this item.
classitems.name: awards

classitems.description:
Schema.org/accessModeSufficient
A list of single or combined accessModes that are sufficient to understand all the intellectual content of a resource. Expected values include:  auditory, tactile, textual, visual.
classitems.name: accessModeSufficient

classitems.description:
Schema.org/producer
The person or organization who produced the work (e.g. music album, movie, tv/radio series etc.).
classitems.name: producer

classitems.description:
Schema.org/editor
Specifies the Person who edited the CreativeWork.
classitems.name: editor

classitems.description:
Schema.org/locationCreated
The location where the CreativeWork was created, which may not be the same as the location depicted in the CreativeWork.
classitems.name: locationCreated

classitems.description:
Schema.org/about
The subject matter of the content.
classitems.name: about

classitems.description:
Schema.org/audio
An embedded audio object.
classitems.name: audio

classitems.description:
Schema.org/encodings
A media object that encodes this CreativeWork.
classitems.name: encodings

classitems.description:
Schema.org/thumbnailUrl
A thumbnail image relevant to the Thing.
classitems.name: thumbnailUrl

classitems.description:

A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.
classitems.name: funder

classitems.description:
Schema.org/typicalAgeRange
The typical expected age range, e.g. '7-9', '11-'.

classitems.description:

Specifies the Person that is legally accountable for the CreativeWork.
classitems.name: accountablePerson

classitems.description:
Schema.org/learningResourceType
The predominant type or kind characterizing the learning resource. For example, 'presentation', 'handout'.
classitems.name: learningResourceType

classitems.description:
Schema.org/material
A material that something is made from, e.g. leather, wool, cotton, paper.
classitems.name: material

classitems.description:
Schema.org/interactivityType
The predominant mode of learning supported by the learning resource. Acceptable values are 'active', 'expositive', or 'mixed'.
classitems.name: interactivityType

classitems.description:

The author of this content or rating. Please note that author is special in that HTML 5 provides a special mechanism for indicating authorship via the rel tag. That is equivalent to this and may be used interchangeably.
classitems.name: author

classitems.description:
Schema.org/accessibilityHazard
A characteristic of the described resource that is physiologically dangerous to some users. Related to WCAG 2.0 guideline 2.3 ([WebSchemas wiki lists possible values](http://www.w3.org/wiki/WebSchemas/Accessibility)).
classitems.name: accessibilityHazard

classitems.description:
Schema.org/sourceOrganization
The Organization on whose behalf the creator was working.
classitems.name: sourceOrganization

classitems.description:

A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.
classitems.name: sponsor

classitems.description:
Schema.org/provider
The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.
classitems.name: provider

classitems.description:
Schema.org/copyrightHolder
The party holding the legal copyright to the CreativeWork.
classitems.name: copyrightHolder

classitems.description:

Indicates that the resource is compatible with the referenced accessibility API ([WebSchemas wiki lists possible values](http://www.w3.org/wiki/WebSchemas/Accessibility)).
classitems.name: accessibilityAPI

classitems.description:
Schema.org/text
The textual content of this CreativeWork.
classitems.name: text

classitems.description:
Schema.org/comment
Comments, typically from users.
classitems.name: comment

classitems.description:
Schema.org/datePublished
Date of first broadcast/publication.
classitems.name: datePublished

classitems.description:
Schema.org/spatialCoverage
The spatialCoverage of a CreativeWork indicates the place(s) which are the focus of the content. It is a subproperty of
     contentLocation intended primarily for more technical and detailed materials. For example with a Dataset, it indicates
     areas that the dataset describes: a dataset of New York weather would have spatialCoverage which was the place: the state of New York.
classitems.name: spatialCoverage

classitems.description:
Schema.org/aggregateRating
The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.
classitems.name: aggregateRating

classitems.description:
Schema.org/educationalAlignment
An alignment to an established educational framework.
classitems.name: educationalAlignment

classitems.description:
Schema.org/video
An embedded video object.
classitems.name: video

classitems.description:
Schema.org/version
The version of the CreativeWork embodied by a specified resource.
classitems.name: version

classitems.description:
Schema.org/mainEntity
Indicates the primary entity described in some page or other CreativeWork.
classitems.name: mainEntity

classitems.description:

A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for encoding.

classitems.name: gtin14

classitems.description:
Schema.org/gtin13
The [GTIN-13](http://apps.gs1.org/GDD/glossary/Pages/GTIN-13.aspx) code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceeding zero. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.
classitems.name: gtin13

classitems.description:
Schema.org/gtin12
The [GTIN-12](http://apps.gs1.org/GDD/glossary/Pages/GTIN-12.aspx) code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.
classitems.name: gtin12

The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

Schema.org/target

Other co-agents that participated in the action indirectly. e.g. John wrote a book with *Steve*.
classitems.name: participant

classitems.description:
Schema.org/instrument
The object that helped the agent perform the action. e.g. John wrote a book with *a pen*.
classitems.name: instrument

classitems.description:
Schema.org/agent
The direct performer or driver of the action (animate or inanimate). e.g. *John* wrote a book.
classitems.name: agent

classitems.description:
Schema.org/object
The object upon which the action is carried out, whose state is kept intact or changed. Also known as the semantic roles patient, affected or undergoer (which change their state) or theme (which doesn't). e.g. John read *a book*.
classitems.name: object

classitems.description:
Schema.org/actionStatus

classitems.description:

For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.
classitems.name: endTime

classitems.description: Schema.org/openingHours The general opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'. * Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: ```Mo```, ```Tu```, ```We```, ```Th```, ```Fr```, ```Sa```, ```Su```. * Times are specified using 24:00 time. For example, 3pm is specified as ```15:00```. * Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>. * If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.

     including [ambiguous symbols](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_sign#Currencies_that_use_the_dollar_or_peso_sign) such as '$' in the value.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
* Note that both [RDFa](http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-primer/#using-the-content-attribute) and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.

classitems.description: Schema.org/openingHours The general opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'. * Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: ```Mo```, ```Tu```, ```We```, ```Th```, ```Fr```, ```Sa```, ```Su```. * Times are specified using 24:00 time. For example, 3pm is specified as ```15:00```. * Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>. * If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.

The type or material of the interior of the vehicle (e.g. synthetic fabric, leather, wood, etc.). While most interior types are characterized by the material used, an interior type can also be based on vehicle usage or target audience.
classitems.name: vehicleInteriorType

classitems.description:
Schema.org/vehicleTransmission
The type of component used for transmitting the power from a rotating power source to the wheels or other relevant component(s) ("gearbox" for cars).
classitems.name: vehicleTransmission

classitems.description:
Schema.org/vehicleSeatingCapacity
The number of passengers that can be seated in the vehicle, both in terms of the physical space available, and in terms of limitations set by law.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62 for persons.
classitems.name: vehicleSeatingCapacity

classitems.description:
Schema.org/cargoVolume
The available volume for cargo or luggage. For automobiles, this is usually the trunk volume.

Typical unit code(s): LTR for liters, FTQ for cubic foot/feet

Note: You can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.
classitems.name: cargoVolume

classitems.description:
Schema.org/knownVehicleDamages
A textual description of known damages, both repaired and unrepaired.
classitems.name: knownVehicleDamages

classitems.description:
Schema.org/vehicleEngine
Information about the engine or engines of the vehicle.
classitems.name: vehicleEngine

classitems.description:
Schema.org/purchaseDate
The date the item e.g. vehicle was purchased by the current owner.
classitems.name: purchaseDate

classitems.description:
Schema.org/vehicleConfiguration
A short text indicating the configuration of the vehicle, e.g. '5dr hatchback ST 2.5 MT 225 hp' or 'limited edition'.
classitems.name: vehicleConfiguration

classitems.description:
Schema.org/vehicleIdentificationNumber
The Vehicle Identification Number (VIN) is a unique serial number used by the automotive industry to identify individual motor vehicles.
classitems.name: vehicleIdentificationNumber

classitems.description:
Schema.org/productionDate
The date of production of the item, e.g. vehicle.
classitems.name: productionDate

classitems.description:
Schema.org/vehicleModelDate
The release date of a vehicle model (often used to differentiate versions of the same make and model).
classitems.name: vehicleModelDate

classitems.description:
Schema.org/fuelConsumption
The amount of fuel consumed for traveling a particular distance or temporal duration with the given vehicle (e.g. liters per 100 km).

* Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for liters per 100 km.  Use [[unitText]] to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. L/100 km.
* Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, [[fuelConsumption]] (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and [[fuelEfficiency]] (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
* Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed ("at 80 km/h") or usage pattern ("city traffic"). You can use [[valueReference]] to link the value for the fuel consumption to another value.
classitems.name: fuelConsumption

classitems.description:
Schema.org/numberOfAirbags
The number or type of airbags in the vehicle.
classitems.name: numberOfAirbags

classitems.description:
Schema.org/numberOfPreviousOwners
The number of owners of the vehicle, including the current one.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62
classitems.name: numberOfPreviousOwners

classitems.description:
Schema.org/numberOfForwardGears
The total number of forward gears available for the transmission system of the vehicle.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62
classitems.name: numberOfForwardGears

classitems.description:
Schema.org/dateVehicleFirstRegistered
The date of the first registration of the vehicle with the respective public authorities.
classitems.name: dateVehicleFirstRegistered

classitems.description:
Schema.org/mileageFromOdometer
The total distance travelled by the particular vehicle since its initial production, as read from its odometer.\n\nTypical unit code(s): KMT for kilometers, SMI for statute miles
classitems.name: mileageFromOdometer

classitems.description:
Schema.org/fuelEfficiency
The distance traveled per unit of fuel used; most commonly miles per gallon (mpg) or kilometers per liter (km/L).

* Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for miles per gallon or kilometers per liter. Use [[unitText]] to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. mpg or km/L.
* Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, [[fuelConsumption]] (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and [[fuelEfficiency]] (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
* Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed ("at 80 km/h") or usage pattern ("city traffic"). You can use [[valueReference]] to link the value for the fuel economy to another value.
classitems.name: fuelEfficiency

classitems.description:
Schema.org/fuelType
The type of fuel suitable for the engine or engines of the vehicle. If the vehicle has only one engine, this property can be attached directly to the vehicle.
classitems.name: fuelType

classitems.description:
Schema.org/steeringPosition
The position of the steering wheel or similar device (mostly for cars).
classitems.name: steeringPosition

classitems.description:
Schema.org/numberOfAxles
The number of axles.\n\nTypical unit code(s): C62
classitems.name: numberOfAxles

classitems.description:
Schema.org/vehicleSpecialUsage
Indicates whether the vehicle has been used for special purposes, like commercial rental, driving school, or as a taxi. The legislation in many countries requires this information to be revealed when offering a car for sale.
classitems.name: vehicleSpecialUsage

classitems.description:
Schema.org/serialNumber
The serial number or any alphanumeric identifier of a particular product. When attached to an offer, it is a shortcut for the serial number of the product included in the offer.
classitems.name: serialNumber

classitems.description:
Schema.org/fromLocation
A sub property of location. The original location of the object or the agent before the action.
classitems.name: fromLocation

classitems.description:
Schema.org/toLocation
A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.
classitems.name: toLocation

classitems.description:
Schema.org/expectsAcceptanceOf
An Offer which must be accepted before the user can perform the Action. For example, the user may need to buy a movie before being able to watch it.
classitems.name: expectsAcceptanceOf

classitems.description:
Schema.org/targetCollection
A sub property of object. The collection target of the action.
classitems.name: targetCollection

classitems.description:
Schema.org/collection
A sub property of object. The collection target of the action.
classitems.name: collection

classitems.description:
Schema.org/fromLocation
A sub property of location. The original location of the object or the agent before the action.
classitems.name: fromLocation

classitems.description:
Schema.org/toLocation
A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.
classitems.name: toLocation

classitems.description:
Schema.org/audience
An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.
classitems.name: audience

classitems.description:
Schema.org/event
Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.
classitems.name: event

classitems.description:
Schema.org/priceSpecification
One or more detailed price specifications, indicating the unit price and delivery or payment charges.
classitems.name: priceSpecification

classitems.description:
Schema.org/price
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

Usage guidelines:

* Use the [[priceCurrency]] property (with [ISO 4217 codes](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217#Active_codes) e.g. "USD") instead of
     including [ambiguous symbols](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_sign#Currencies_that_use_the_dollar_or_peso_sign) such as '$' in the value.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
* Note that both [RDFa](http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-primer/#using-the-content-attribute) and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
classitems.name: price

classitems.description:
Schema.org/query
A sub property of instrument. The query used on this action.
classitems.name: query

classitems.description:
Schema.org/awayTeam
The away team in a sports event.
classitems.name: awayTeam

classitems.description:
Schema.org/competitor
A competitor in a sports event.
classitems.name: competitor

classitems.description:
Schema.org/homeTeam
The home team in a sports event.
classitems.name: homeTeam

classitems.description:
Schema.org/accessCode
Password, PIN, or access code needed for delivery (e.g. from a locker).
classitems.name: accessCode

classitems.description:
Schema.org/availableFrom
When the item is available for pickup from the store, locker, etc.
classitems.name: availableFrom

classitems.description:
Schema.org/availableThrough
After this date, the item will no longer be available for pickup.
classitems.name: availableThrough

classitems.description:
Schema.org/hasDeliveryMethod
Method used for delivery or shipping.
classitems.name: hasDeliveryMethod

classitems.description:
Schema.org/courseMode
The medium or means of delivery of the course instance or the mode of study, either as a text label (e.g. "online", "onsite" or "blended"; "synchronous" or "asynchronous"; "full-time" or "part-time") or as a URL reference to a term from a controlled vocabulary (e.g. https://ceds.ed.gov/element/001311#Asynchronous ).
classitems.name: courseMode

classitems.description:
Schema.org/instructor
A person assigned to instruct or provide instructional assistance for the [[CourseInstance]].
classitems.name: instructor

classitems.description:
Schema.org/isAccessibleForFree
A flag to signal that the publication is accessible for free.
classitems.name: isAccessibleForFree

classitems.description:
Schema.org/publishedOn
A broadcast service associated with the publication event.
classitems.name: publishedOn

classitems.description:
Schema.org/free
A flag to signal that the publication or event is accessible for free.
classitems.name: free

classitems.description:
Schema.org/subtitleLanguage
Languages in which subtitles/captions are available, in [IETF BCP 47 standard format](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).
classitems.name: subtitleLanguage

classitems.description:
Schema.org/videoFormat
The type of screening or video broadcast used (e.g. IMAX, 3D, SD, HD, etc.).
classitems.name: videoFormat

classitems.description:
Schema.org/workPresented
The movie presented during this event.
classitems.name: workPresented

classitems.description:
Schema.org/bed
The type of bed or beds included in the accommodation. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you use bed directly with a text.
     If you want to indicate the quantity of a certain kind of bed, use an instance of BedDetails. For more detailed information, use the amenityFeature property.
classitems.name: bed

classitems.description:
Schema.org/numberOfRooms
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the acccommodation or lodging business.
 Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.
classitems.name: numberOfRooms

classitems.description:
Schema.org/occupancy
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
 Typical unit code(s): C62 for person
classitems.name: occupancy

classitems.description:
Schema.org/numberOfRooms
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the acccommodation or lodging business.
 Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.
classitems.name: numberOfRooms

classitems.description:
Schema.org/numberOfRooms
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the acccommodation or lodging business.
 Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.
classitems.name: numberOfRooms

classitems.description:
Schema.org/occupancy
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
 Typical unit code(s): C62 for person
classitems.name: occupancy

classitems.description:
Schema.org/iataCode
IATA identifier for an airline or airport.
classitems.name: iataCode

classitems.description:
Schema.org/icaoCode
ICAO identifier for an airport.
classitems.name: icaoCode

classitems.description:
Schema.org/reviewCount
The count of total number of reviews.
classitems.name: reviewCount

classitems.description:
Schema.org/itemReviewed
The item that is being reviewed/rated.
classitems.name: itemReviewed

classitems.description:
Schema.org/ratingCount
The count of total number of ratings.
classitems.name: ratingCount

classitems.description:
Schema.org/characterName
The name of a character played in some acting or performing role, i.e. in a PerformanceRole.
classitems.name: characterName

classitems.description:
Schema.org/numberedPosition
A number associated with a role in an organization, for example, the number on an athlete's jersey.
classitems.name: numberedPosition

classitems.description:
Schema.org/educationalRole
An educationalRole of an EducationalAudience.
classitems.name: educationalRole

classitems.description:
Schema.org/yearlyRevenue
The size of the business in annual revenue.
classitems.name: yearlyRevenue

classitems.description:
Schema.org/numberOfEmployees
The number of employees in an organization e.g. business.
classitems.name: numberOfEmployees

classitems.description:
Schema.org/yearsInOperation
The age of the business.
classitems.name: yearsInOperation

classitems.description:
Schema.org/suggestedMaxAge
Maximal age recommended for viewing content.
classitems.name: suggestedMaxAge

classitems.description:
Schema.org/requiredMinAge
Audiences defined by a person's minimum age.
classitems.name: requiredMinAge

classitems.description:
Schema.org/suggestedMinAge
Minimal age recommended for viewing content.
classitems.name: suggestedMinAge

classitems.description:
Schema.org/requiredMaxAge
Audiences defined by a person's maximum age.
classitems.name: requiredMaxAge

classitems.description:
Schema.org/suggestedGender
The gender of the person or audience.
classitems.name: suggestedGender

classitems.description:
Schema.org/requiredGender
Audiences defined by a person's gender.
classitems.name: requiredGender

classitems.description:
Schema.org/feesAndCommissionsSpecification
Description of fees, commissions, and other terms applied either to a class of financial product, or by a financial service organization.
classitems.name: feesAndCommissionsSpecification

classitems.description:
Schema.org/annualPercentageRate
The annual rate that is charged for borrowing (or made by investing), expressed as a single percentage number that represents the actual yearly cost of funds over the term of a loan. This includes any fees or additional costs associated with the transaction.
classitems.name: annualPercentageRate

classitems.description:
Schema.org/interestRate
The interest rate, charged or paid, applicable to the financial product. Note: This is different from the calculated annualPercentageRate.
classitems.name: interestRate

classitems.description:
Schema.org/serviceOperator
The operating organization, if different from the provider.  This enables the representation of services that are provided by an organization, but operated by another organization like a subcontractor.
classitems.name: serviceOperator

classitems.description:
Schema.org/broadcastTimezone
The timezone in [ISO 8601 format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601) for which the service bases its broadcasts
classitems.name: broadcastTimezone

classitems.description:
Schema.org/area
The area within which users can expect to reach the broadcast service.
classitems.name: area

classitems.description:
Schema.org/videoFormat
The type of screening or video broadcast used (e.g. IMAX, 3D, SD, HD, etc.).
classitems.name: videoFormat

classitems.description:
Schema.org/broadcastDisplayName
The name displayed in the channel guide. For many US affiliates, it is the network name.
classitems.name: broadcastDisplayName

classitems.description:
Schema.org/broadcastAffiliateOf
The media network(s) whose content is broadcast on this station.
classitems.name: broadcastAffiliateOf

classitems.description:
Schema.org/parentService
A broadcast service to which the broadcast service may belong to such as regional variations of a national channel.
classitems.name: parentService

classitems.description:
Schema.org/broadcaster
The organization owning or operating the broadcast service.
classitems.name: broadcaster

classitems.description:
Schema.org/interactionService
The WebSite or SoftwareApplication where the interactions took place.
classitems.name: interactionService

classitems.description:
Schema.org/userInteractionCount
The number of interactions for the CreativeWork using the WebSite or SoftwareApplication.
classitems.name: userInteractionCount

classitems.description:
Schema.org/interactionType
The Action representing the type of interaction. For up votes, +1s, etc. use [[LikeAction]]. For down votes use [[DislikeAction]]. Otherwise, use the most specific Action.
classitems.name: interactionType

classitems.description:
Schema.org/postalCode
The postal code. For example, 94043.
classitems.name: postalCode

classitems.description:
Schema.org/latitude
The latitude of a location. For example ```37.42242``` ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)).
classitems.name: latitude

classitems.description:
Schema.org/elevation
The elevation of a location ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)).
classitems.name: elevation

classitems.description:
Schema.org/longitude
The longitude of a location. For example ```-122.08585``` ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)).
classitems.name: longitude

classitems.description:
Schema.org/addressCountry
The country. For example, USA. You can also provide the two-letter [ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1).
classitems.name: addressCountry

classitems.description:
Schema.org/address
Physical address of the item.
classitems.name: address

classitems.description:
Schema.org/opens
The opening hour of the place or service on the given day(s) of the week.
classitems.name: opens

classitems.description:
Schema.org/dayOfWeek
The day of the week for which these opening hours are valid.
classitems.name: dayOfWeek

classitems.description:
Schema.org/validFrom
The date when the item becomes valid.
classitems.name: validFrom

classitems.description:
Schema.org/closes
The closing hour of the place or service on the given day(s) of the week.
classitems.name: closes

classitems.description:
Schema.org/validThrough
The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.
classitems.name: validThrough

classitems.description:
Schema.org/priceCurrency
The currency (in 3-letter ISO 4217 format) of the price or a price component, when attached to [[PriceSpecification]] and its subtypes.
classitems.name: priceCurrency

classitems.description:
Schema.org/validFrom
The date when the item becomes valid.
classitems.name: validFrom

classitems.description:
Schema.org/price
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

Usage guidelines:

* Use the [[priceCurrency]] property (with [ISO 4217 codes](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217#Active_codes) e.g. "USD") instead of
     including [ambiguous symbols](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_sign#Currencies_that_use_the_dollar_or_peso_sign) such as '$' in the value.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
* Note that both [RDFa](http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-primer/#using-the-content-attribute) and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
classitems.name: price

classitems.description:
Schema.org/minPrice
The lowest price if the price is a range.
classitems.name: minPrice

classitems.description:
Schema.org/eligibleTransactionVolume
The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.
classitems.name: eligibleTransactionVolume

classitems.description:
Schema.org/validThrough
The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.
classitems.name: validThrough

classitems.description:
Schema.org/valueAddedTaxIncluded
Specifies whether the applicable value-added tax (VAT) is included in the price specification or not.
classitems.name: valueAddedTaxIncluded

classitems.description:
Schema.org/eligibleQuantity
The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.
classitems.name: eligibleQuantity

classitems.description:
Schema.org/maxPrice
The highest price if the price is a range.
classitems.name: maxPrice

classitems.description:
Schema.org/ownedThrough
The date and time of giving up ownership on the product.
classitems.name: ownedThrough

classitems.description:
Schema.org/acquiredFrom
The organization or person from which the product was acquired.
classitems.name: acquiredFrom

classitems.description:
Schema.org/typeOfGood
The product that this structured value is referring to.
classitems.name: typeOfGood

classitems.description:
Schema.org/ownedFrom
The date and time of obtaining the product.
classitems.name: ownedFrom

classitems.description:
Schema.org/calories
The number of calories.
classitems.name: calories

classitems.description:
Schema.org/fiberContent
The number of grams of fiber.
classitems.name: fiberContent

classitems.description:
Schema.org/sugarContent
The number of grams of sugar.
classitems.name: sugarContent

classitems.description:
Schema.org/cholesterolContent
The number of milligrams of cholesterol.
classitems.name: cholesterolContent

classitems.description:
Schema.org/proteinContent
The number of grams of protein.
classitems.name: proteinContent

classitems.description:
Schema.org/fatContent
The number of grams of fat.
classitems.name: fatContent

classitems.description:
Schema.org/transFatContent
The number of grams of trans fat.
classitems.name: transFatContent

classitems.description:
Schema.org/carbohydrateContent
The number of grams of carbohydrates.
classitems.name: carbohydrateContent

classitems.description:
Schema.org/unsaturatedFatContent
The number of grams of unsaturated fat.
classitems.name: unsaturatedFatContent

classitems.description:
Schema.org/saturatedFatContent
The number of grams of saturated fat.
classitems.name: saturatedFatContent

classitems.description:
Schema.org/sodiumContent
The number of milligrams of sodium.
classitems.name: sodiumContent

classitems.description:
Schema.org/servingSize
The serving size, in terms of the number of volume or mass.
classitems.name: servingSize

classitems.description:
Schema.org/postalCode
The postal code. For example, 94043.
classitems.name: postalCode

classitems.description:
Schema.org/elevation
The elevation of a location ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)).
classitems.name: elevation

classitems.description:
Schema.org/line
A line is a point-to-point path consisting of two or more points. A line is expressed as a series of two or more point objects separated by space.
classitems.name: line

classitems.description:
Schema.org/addressCountry
The country. For example, USA. You can also provide the two-letter [ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1).
classitems.name: addressCountry

classitems.description:
Schema.org/address
Physical address of the item.
classitems.name: address

classitems.description:
Schema.org/polygon
A polygon is the area enclosed by a point-to-point path for which the starting and ending points are the same. A polygon is expressed as a series of four or more space delimited points where the first and final points are identical.
classitems.name: polygon

classitems.description:
Schema.org/box
A box is the area enclosed by the rectangle formed by two points. The first point is the lower corner, the second point is the upper corner. A box is expressed as two points separated by a space character.
classitems.name: box

classitems.description:
Schema.org/circle
A circle is the circular region of a specified radius centered at a specified latitude and longitude. A circle is expressed as a pair followed by a radius in meters.
classitems.name: circle

classitems.description:
Schema.org/unitCode
The unit of measurement given using the UN/CEFACT Common Code (3 characters) or a URL. Other codes than the UN/CEFACT Common Code may be used with a prefix followed by a colon.
classitems.name: unitCode

classitems.description:
Schema.org/minValue
The lower value of some characteristic or property.
classitems.name: minValue

classitems.description: Schema.org/unitText A string or text indicating the unit of measurement. Useful if you cannot provide a standard unit code for unitCode.
classitems.name: unitText

classitems.description:
Schema.org/valueReference
A pointer to a secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature.
classitems.name: valueReference

classitems.description:
Schema.org/propertyID
A commonly used identifier for the characteristic represented by the property, e.g. a manufacturer or a standard code for a property. propertyID can be
 (1) a prefixed string, mainly meant to be used with standards for product properties; (2) a site-specific, non-prefixed string (e.g. the primary key of the property or the vendor-specific id of the property), or (3)
 a URL indicating the type of the property, either pointing to an external vocabulary, or a Web resource that describes the property (e.g. a glossary entry).
 Standards bodies should promote a standard prefix for the identifiers of properties from their standards.
classitems.name: propertyID

classitems.description:
Schema.org/value
The value of the quantitative value or property value node.

* For [[QuantitativeValue]] and [[MonetaryAmount]], the recommended type for values is 'Number'.
* For [[PropertyValue]], it can be 'Text;', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.
classitems.name: value

classitems.description:
Schema.org/maxValue
The upper value of some characteristic or property.
classitems.name: maxValue

classitems.description:
Schema.org/durationOfWarranty
The duration of the warranty promise. Common unitCode values are ANN for year, MON for months, or DAY for days.
classitems.name: durationOfWarranty

classitems.description:
Schema.org/warrantyScope
The scope of the warranty promise.
classitems.name: warrantyScope

classitems.description:
Schema.org/contactType
A person or organization can have different contact points, for different purposes. For example, a sales contact point, a PR contact point and so on. This property is used to specify the kind of contact point.
classitems.name: contactType

classitems.description:
Schema.org/faxNumber
The fax number.
classitems.name: faxNumber

classitems.description:
Schema.org/productSupported
The product or service this support contact point is related to (such as product support for a particular product line). This can be a specific product or product line (e.g. "iPhone") or a general category of products or services (e.g. "smartphones").
classitems.name: productSupported

classitems.description:
Schema.org/availableLanguage
A language someone may use with the item. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[inLanguage]]
classitems.name: availableLanguage

classitems.description:
Schema.org/areaServed
The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.
classitems.name: areaServed

classitems.description:
Schema.org/hoursAvailable
The hours during which this service or contact is available.
classitems.name: hoursAvailable

classitems.description:

If `Buffer.TYPED_ARRAY_SUPPORT`:
  === true    Use Uint8Array implementation (fastest)
  === false   Use Object implementation (most compatible, even IE6)

Browsers that support typed arrays are IE 10+, Firefox 4+, Chrome 7+, Safari 5.1+,
Opera 11.6+, iOS 4.2+.

Due to various browser bugs, sometimes the Object implementation will be used even
when the browser supports typed arrays.

Note:

  - Firefox 4-29 lacks support for adding new properties to `Uint8Array` instances,
    See: https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=695438.

  - Chrome 9-10 is missing the `TypedArray.prototype.subarray` function.

  - IE10 has a broken `TypedArray.prototype.subarray` function which returns arrays of
    incorrect length in some situations.

We detect these buggy browsers and set `Buffer.TYPED_ARRAY_SUPPORT` to `false` so they
get the Object implementation, which is slower but behaves correctly.

The Buffer constructor returns instances of `Uint8Array` that have their
prototype changed to `Buffer.prototype`. Furthermore, `Buffer` is a subclass of
`Uint8Array`, so the returned instances will have all the node `Buffer` methods
and the `Uint8Array` methods. Square bracket notation works as expected -- it
returns a single octet.

The `Uint8Array` prototype remains unmodified.

Functionally equivalent to Buffer(arg, encoding) but throws a TypeError
if value is a number.

Constructor for an ArrayBuffer-backed byte buffer.

The buffer may be constructed from a string, an ArrayBuffer, DataView, or a
TypedArray.

If a string is given, its encoding should be provided as an option,
otherwise it will default to 'binary'. A 'binary' string is encoded such
that each character is one byte in length and size.

If an ArrayBuffer, DataView, or TypedArray is given, it will be used
*directly* without any copying. Note that, if a write to the buffer requires
more space, the buffer will allocate a new backing ArrayBuffer to
accommodate. The starting read and write offsets for the buffer may be
given as options.

Missing item type
Stores an item on local disk.

The available types of local storage include 'flash', 'web', and 'both'.

The type 'flash' refers to flash local storage (SharedObject). In order
to use flash local storage, the 'api' parameter must be valid. The type
'web' refers to WebStorage, if supported by the browser. The type 'both'
refers to storing using both 'flash' and 'web', not just one or the
other.

The location array should list the storage types to use in order of
preference:

['flash']: flash only storage
['web']: web only storage
['both']: try to store in both
['flash','web']: store in flash first, but if not available, 'web'
['web','flash']: store in web first, but if not available, 'flash'

The location array defaults to: ['web', 'flash']

Performs RSA encryption.

The parameter bt controls whether to put padding bytes before the
message passed in. Set bt to either true or false to disable padding
completely (in order to handle e.g. EMSA-PSS encoding seperately before),
signaling whether the encryption operation is a public key operation
(i.e. encrypting data) or not, i.e. private key operation (data signing).

For PKCS#1 v1.5 padding pass in the block type to use, i.e. either 0x01
(for signing) or 0x02 (for encryption). The key operation mode (private
or public) is derived from this flag in that case).
